{"title_page": "Pape Diouf", "text_new": "{{short description|Senegalese journalist}}\n{{for2|the musician|[[Pape Diouf (artist)]]|the footballer who is a goalkeeper|[[Pape Mamadou Diouf]]|the footballer who is a winger/striker|[[Pape Pat\u00e9 Diouf]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Mababa Pape Diouf\n| image =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1951|12|18}}\n| death_date = {{death date_and_age|df=yes|2020|3|31|1951|12|18}}\n| birth_place = [[Ab\u00e9ch\u00e9]], Chad\n| death_place = [[Dakar]], Senegal\n}}\n'''Mababa \"Pape\" Diouf''' (18 December 1951 \u2013 31 March 2020) was a Senegalese [[journalist]], best known for being the president of French football club [[Olympique de Marseille]]<ref name=\"OM\">{{in lang|fr}} [In] OM Actualit\u00e9s (retrieved : 1 May 2012) [http://om-act.football.fr/?q=Pape+Diouf&x=0&y=0]</ref> between 2005 and 2009.<ref name=\"OMmag\">{{in lang|fr}} Exclusive interview with Olympique de Marseille Magazine (official site) [http://www.om.net/fr/Saison/101002/Actualites/36542/Pape_Diouf_L_OM_ne_fait_plus_dans_le_folklore \"Pape Diouf : L\u2019OM ne fait plus dans le folklore\"] (Retrieved : 1 May 2012)</ref>\n\nDiouf was born in [[Ab\u00e9ch\u00e9]], [[Chad]], to Senegalese parents. The family returned to their native country shortly after Diouf's birth.\n\n==Career==\nDiouf moved to [[Marseille]] at the age of eighteen. He eventually became a journalist for a city newspaper.<ref name=\"OMmag\"/> Diouf centred his work around sport, and particularly the local football club, [[Olympique de Marseille]].<ref name=\"OM\"/><ref name=\"OMmag\"/> Eventually he turned his hand to being a sports agent,<ref name=\"OMmag\"/> with clients such as former French international defender [[Basile Boli]], and Cameroonian goalkeeper [[Joseph-Antoine Bell]] playing for Marseille. He became closely linked with the [[C\u00f4te d'Azur]] side, and his intimate relationship with the club culminated in him becoming club president in 2005. [[Robert Louis-Dreyfus]] announced that Pape Diouf would leave on 17 June 2009.<ref>[http://www.om.net/fr/Saison/101002/Actualites/40708/Communique_de_R_Louis_Dreyfus Press release from Robert Louis Dreyfus]</ref> He was replaced by [[Jean-Claude Dassier]].\n\n==Death==\n\nDiouf died on 31 March 2020 after succumbing to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global pandemic]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Senegal|Senegal]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC Sport|title=Pape Diouf: Former Marseille president dies after contracting coronavirus|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52117676|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.sport.fr/football/pape-diouf-6735.shtm Sport fr] (retrieved : 1 May 2012)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal|Sports|Senegal}}\n\n{{Olympique de Marseille}}\n{{Serer topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diouf, Pape}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ouadda\u00ef Region]]\n[[Category:Olympique de Marseille chairmen]]\n[[Category:Senegalese journalists]]\n[[Category:Association football agents]]\n[[Category:Serer journalists]]\n[[Category:Serer sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po Aix alumni]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriates in Chad]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Senegal]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Senegalese journalist}}\n{{for2|the musician|[[Pape Diouf (artist)]]|the footballer who is a goalkeeper|[[Pape Mamadou Diouf]]|the footballer who is a winger/striker|[[Pape Pat\u00e9 Diouf]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Mababa Pape Diouf\n| image =\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1951|12|18}}\n| death_date = {{death date_and_age|df=yes|2020|3|31|1951|12|18}}\n| birth_place = [[Ab\u00e9ch\u00e9]], Chad\n| death_place = [[Dakar]], Senegal\n}}\n'''Mababa \"Pape\" Diouf''' (December 18, 1951 \u2013 March 31, 2020) was a Senegalese [[journalist]], best known for being the president of French football club [[Olympique de Marseille]]<ref name=\"OM\">{{in lang|fr}} [In] OM Actualit\u00e9s (retrieved : 1 May 2012) [http://om-act.football.fr/?q=Pape+Diouf&x=0&y=0]</ref> between 2005 and 2009.<ref name=\"OMmag\">{{in lang|fr}} Exclusive interview with Olympique de Marseille Magazine (official site) [http://www.om.net/fr/Saison/101002/Actualites/36542/Pape_Diouf_L_OM_ne_fait_plus_dans_le_folklore \"Pape Diouf : L\u2019OM ne fait plus dans le folklore\"] (Retrieved : 1 May 2012)</ref>\n\nDiouf was born in [[Ab\u00e9ch\u00e9]], [[Chad]], to Senegalese parents. The family returned to their native country shortly after Diouf's birth.\n\n==Career==\nDiouf moved to [[Marseille]] at the age of eighteen. He eventually became a journalist for a city newspaper.<ref name=\"OMmag\"/> Diouf centred his work around sport, and particularly the local football club, [[Olympique de Marseille]].<ref name=\"OM\"/><ref name=\"OMmag\"/> Eventually he turned his hand to being a sports agent,<ref name=\"OMmag\"/> with clients such as former French international defender [[Basile Boli]], and Cameroonian goalkeeper [[Joseph-Antoine Bell]] playing for Marseille. He became closely linked with the [[C\u00f4te d'Azur]] side, and his intimate relationship with the club culminated in him becoming club president in 2005. [[Robert Louis-Dreyfus]] announced that Pape Diouf would leave on 17 June 2009.<ref>[http://www.om.net/fr/Saison/101002/Actualites/40708/Communique_de_R_Louis_Dreyfus Press release from Robert Louis Dreyfus]</ref> He was replaced by [[Jean-Claude Dassier]].\n\n==Death==\n\nDiouf died on 31 March 2020 after succumbing to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|global pandemic]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Senegal|Senegal]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=BBC Sport|title=Pape Diouf: Former Marseille president dies after contracting coronavirus|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/52117676|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{in lang|fr}} [http://www.sport.fr/football/pape-diouf-6735.shtm Sport fr] (retrieved : 1 May 2012)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Portal|Sports|Senegal}}\n\n{{Olympique de Marseille}}\n{{Serer topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diouf, Pape}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ouadda\u00ef Region]]\n[[Category:Olympique de Marseille chairmen]]\n[[Category:Senegalese journalists]]\n[[Category:Association football agents]]\n[[Category:Serer journalists]]\n[[Category:Serer sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po Aix alumni]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriates in Chad]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Senegal]]\n", "name_user": "Joseph2302", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pape_Diouf"}
{"title_page": "2021 Hyndburn Borough Council election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Hyndburn Borough Council election, 2021\n| type = parliamentary\n| previous_election = 2019_Hyndburn_Borough_Council_election\n| previous_year = 2019\n| next_election = 2022_Hyndburn_Borough_Council_election\n| next_year = 2022\n| seats_for_election = 12 of 35 seats to Hyndburn Borough Council\n| election_date = 6 May 2021\n| majority_seats = 18\n| party1 = Labour Party (UK)\n| seats_before1 = {{nowrap|26}}\n| seats1 = {{nowrap|26}}\n| seat_change1 = {{nowrap|{{steady}}}}\n| party2 = Conservative Party (UK)\n| seats_before2 = {{nowrap|9}}\n| seats2 = {{nowrap|9}}\n| seat_change2 = {{nowrap|{{steady}}}}\n| map_image = Hyndburn UK local election 2016 map.svg\n| map_caption = 2016 local election results in Hyndburn\n{{legend|#dc241f|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]}}\n{{legend|#0087dc|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]}}\n{{legend|#808080|Not contested}}\n| ongoing = \n| leader1 = Miles Parkinson\n| leader2 = TBD\n}}\n\nA by-thirds [[Hyndburn]] Borough Council local election (postponed since March 2020, due to the Coronavirus outbreak), should be held on Thursday 6 May 2021. Approximately one third of the local council's 35 seats fall up for election on that day.<ref name=\"TEC-Notice\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/who-we-are-and-what-we-do/elections-and-referendums |title=Elections & Referendums - what we do |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Electoral Commission}}</ref>\n\nThis election postponed for 12-months since 2020<ref name=\"Previously-postponed-HBC-election\">{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Hyndburn_Borough_Council_election |title=Previously postponed Hyndburn Borough Council election |accessdate=April 1, 2020}}</ref>, should be taking place at the same time as the regularly-scheduled 2021 Lancashire County Council elections.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Background==\nBefore the election [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] had a majority of 26 councillors, [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] had 9 councillors<ref name=\"HBC-Councillors\">{{Cite web|url=https://democracy.hyndburnbc.gov.uk/mgMemberIndex.aspx?FN=PARTY&VW=LIST&PIC=0 |title=Hyndburn Borough Council - Your councillors by political party |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Hyndburn Borough Council}}</ref>\n\nLabour will be defending 10-seats and Conservatives will be defending 2-seats.\n\n==Local Election result==\nThe majority grouping of councillors as the headline result of the election.\n\nAfter the election, the composition of the council's 35 seats was -\n\n*[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] 26\n*[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] 9\n\n{{Election summary begin|title = Hyndburn Local Election Result 2021}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |seats      = 10\n  |gain       = \n  |loss       = \n  |net        = \n  |seats %    = \n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = \n  |plus/minus = \n}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |seats      = 2\n  |gain       = \n  |loss       = \n  |net        = \n  |seats %    = \n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      =\n  |plus/minus =\n}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = UKIP\n  |seats      = 0\n  |gain       = \n  |loss       = \n  |net        = \n  |seats %    = \n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = \n  |plus/minus = \n}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |seats      = 0\n  |gain       = \n  |loss       = \n  |net        = \n  |seats %    = \n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      = \n  |plus/minus = \n}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Spoilt\n  |seats      = \n  |gain       = \n  |loss       = \n  |net        = \n  |seats %    = \n  |votes %    = \n  |votes      =\n  |plus/minus = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\nNB: Four (of 16) Council wards, where seats were NOT be up for re-election in 2021, included the following wards - Clayton Le Moors, Huncoat, Immanuel in Oswaldtwistle and Milnshaw in Accrington. However, as there was ALSO an election for Lancashire's next Police and Crime Commissioner, polling stations in those Four wards would ALSO have been OPEN.\n\nPrevious Councillors who were looking to Stand-Down in May 2021 included - Stephanie Haworth (Lab) (Overton). \n\nAs well as this the Barnfield seat became vacant in March 2020 as Councillor Tony Dobson passed away.\n\n==Ward results==\n\n===Altham===\n{{Election box begin | title=Altham \u2013 Electorate TBC}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Steve BUTTON\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = UKIP\n  |candidate  =\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Green Party of England and Wales\n  |candidate  =\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate|\n  |party      =\n  |candidate  = spoilt votes\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =\n  |change     = \n}}\n {{Election box majority|\n   |votes      =\n   |percentage =\n   |change     = ''N/A''\n }}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Barnfield===\n{{Election box begin | title=Barnfield \u2013 Electorate TBC}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Timothy FENTON\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  =\n  |votes      =\n  |percentage =\n  |change     =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party  